*****[WNV in birds has now spread north to Canada (Ontario) (confirmation
pending) & south to southern Maryland, USA, surpassing its 1999 limits.
(The fact that the ProMED-mail Policy Committee met this week in Toronto is
entirely coincidental.) Cold nights -- less than 60 degrees F -- have
started in downstate New York, restricting mosquito activity. Mod.JW*****
Canada
---------
Date: Thu, 21 Sep 2000 15:51:23 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: The Windsor Star, 21 Sep 2000 [edited

The first possible sign of the deadly West Nile virus in Canada has been
found in a crow in Windsor, indicating the virus may be heading here.
A small amount of genetic material from a virus consistent with West Nile
was detected in a dead crow found 10 Aug 2000, scientists at the federal
government's highly sophisticated laboratory in Winnipeg have confirmed.
Tissue samples from the carcass were sent Wednesday to an American
laboratory experienced in identifying West Nile to try to confirm the
results. The results are expected in a week.
"We want to get a conclusive answer as soon as possible," said Dr. Harvey
Artsob, chief of zoonotic diseases at the Canadian Science Centre for Human
and Animal Health, one of only 12 labs in the world that can handle the
deadliest infections known.
It is a "possible positive," Dr. Allen Heimann, medical officer of health
for Windsor and Essex County, said Wednesday. But Heimann emphasized that
the finding does not mean there is an immediate threat to public health.
More than 600 dead birds across Ontario have been tested since the crow was
found and none have shown signs of the virus. No trace of the virus has been
found in humans, mosquitoes or sentinel chickens during continued monitoring.
The find has surprised and stumped some health officials who have been
monitoring for the virus. They expected it to appear first in the Niagara
Region because of that area's proximity to New York State. However,
surveillance of the virus across New York State shows that it has
"hopscotched" hundreds of km in relatively short periods, said Barker.
It could be that the mosquitoes are being blown by the wind, that infected
birds are migrating or simply that surveillance is inconsistent, he said.
Ontario does only one-fifth the surveillance now being done in New York
State.
[Byline: Anne Jarvis Star Health Sciences Reporter
--
[The time lag in testing means that WNV could be more widespread in Ontario
than it appears at present.  Mod.JW
