Date: Fri, 22 Sep 2000 10:40:23 -0400
From: Karl Kabasele <kkabase@city.toronto.on.ca>
& M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Toronto Star, 21 Sep 2000 [edited
<http://www.thestar.com/back_issues/ED20000921/news/20000921NEW04_CI-NILE21.
htm>

Tests on the bird at a federal laboratory in Winnipeg showed signs of the
virus, but were inconclusive, said Dr. Harvey Artsob, head of Health
Canada's zoonotic diseases. He said tissue has been sent to a lab in the
United States that is experienced in testing for the virus. The results are
expected in about 10 days.
More than 1100 tests have been performed on dead birds across Ontario since
May and this is the only possible case of the virus, said Dr. Colin D'Cunha,
Ontario's chief medical officer of health.
[Byline: Alan Barnes, Toronto Star Staff Reporter
--
Karl J. Kabasele, MD MPH
Senior Community Medicine Resident
Communicable Disease Control
Toronto Public Health
<kkabase@city.toronto.on.ca>
