Connecticut
--------------
State of Connecticut Mosquito Management Program
<http://dep.state.ct.us/mosquito/index.asp> [edited

On 22 Sep 2000, the State announced a crow testing positive for West Nile
Virus in the town of Plainville. There will be no spraying in the town of
Plainville. Residents are asked to limit their exposure to mosquito bites
and to reduce standing water around their homes.
*****************
Maryland
------------
Date: Fri, 22 Sep 2000 07:39:55 -0400
From: Joseph Scaletta <JScaletta@dhmh.state.md.us>

West Nile Virus, avian cases - Maryland
-----------------------------------
Late Tuesday night, CDC Fort Collins confirmed the presence of West Nile
virus in a crow found in Relay, Maryland near the Baltimore County / Howard
County line. Originally discovered 13 Sep 2000, the bird was obviously quite
ill (unable to stand or perch) and transported to an animal refuge center
where it later died and was submitted to the Department of Health and Mental
Hygiene's Laboratory Administration. Preliminary necropsy findings were
consistent with intercranial lesions notably associated with WNV. Two test
sets of RT-PCR were completed and found to be positive. The specimen was
then forwarded for confirmatory testing to Ft. Collins.
An additional crow, found in Howard County, not far from the index case
has also tested positive and has been sent to CDC for confirmatory testing.
Maryland Department of Agriculture will commence ground spraying the
evening of Fri 22 Sep 2000.
Last year a WNV positive crow was found in Baltimore City. However the
findings contained in this report mark the first evidence of WNV in Maryland
this year.
--
Joseph M. Scaletta
West Nile Surveillance Coordinator, Epidemiologist
Maryland Department of Health and Mental Hygiene
USA
<JScaletta@dhmh.state.md.us>
[We thank Dr Scaletta for this official update, & look forward to seeing a
West Nile website for Maryland.  Mod.JW
