Date: Fri, 22 Sep 2000 12:19:29 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Reuters Online Thu 21 Sep 2000 6:01 PM EST

The mosquito-borne West Nile virus has extended its U.S. range southward
into heavily populated Maryland suburbs, where 2 infected crows were found
dead last week, health officials said on Thursday.
One bird was discovered 15 Sep 2000 in Columbia, about 30 miles (48 km)
northwest of Washington, D.C., while a second turned up two days earlier in
the nearby community of Relay, which lies further north toward Baltimore.
Until now, West Nile virus had not been seen further south than the city of
Baltimore, where an infected crow was discovered last October 1999. The
latest discoveries were the first in Maryland for 2000.
[We also thank H. Larry Penning, MD, of Maryland & Susan Bailey RN BSN,
Chief, Allergy / Immunization / Travel Medicine, DTHC  Pentagon, for
sending us news stories with similar information.  Mod.JW.
