New York State
http://www.health.state.ny.us/nysdoh/westnile/index.htm
West Nile Virus Update - Posted: 22 Sep 2000 [edited

Today, the New York State Health Department's Wadsworth Center laboratories
reported 24 West Nile virus positive dead birds [from a long list of
counties.
Twelve West Nile Virus positive mosquito pools were reported in New York
City: Brooklyn, 3; Manhattan, 1 and Staten Island, 8.
One West Nile Virus positive live wild bird was found in Queens, and 1 West
Nile virus positive domestic rabbit was found in Albany County.
The total number of West Nile virus positive specimens from New York State
for this year is 839 birds, 286 mosquito pools, 1 sentinel chicken, 7 live
wild birds, 14 bats, 1 horse, 1 raccoon, 3 domestic rabbits, 1 chipmunk and
11 human cases.
[A check on the NYS map, updated to 22 Sep 2000,
<http://www.health.state.ny.us/nysdoh/westnile/update/today.gif>
shows only 2 counties (Wayne & Chenango) in the entire state with no
evidence yet of WNV activity. Plus, the map has a list showing the virus
has even killed a macaw & a hummingbird, & is having an impact on dozens of
American bird species, including the House Sparrow & European Starling (16 &
4 cases, respectively) which were at first thought to be circulating virus
without ill effects  Mod.JW.
