Rhode Island
-----------------
http://www.state.ri.us/dem/pr/0918003.htm
For Release: 18 Sep 2000 [edited
Media Contact:
Malcolm Grant 222-6605, cell phone 447-1351
Stephanie Powell 222-4700 ext. 4418, pager 482-2968

The Department of Environmental Management this evening announced the second
finding of West Nile Virus in Westerly. The positive result came from an
American Crow that was collected from Wilcox Park in downtown Westerly on 10
Sep 2000. The bird was tested at the University of Rhode Islands Mosquito
Virus Testing Laboratory. Confirmatory test results were received by DEM at
5:30 p.m. this evening.
DEM also notified Connecticut state officials of the positive finding, since
the birds location was close to the Stonington, CT town line.
Under the states mosquito action plan, testing birds and mosquitoes for
signs of the disease has been ongoing since late May 2000. No mosquitoes
have tested positive for West Nile Virus or Eastern Equine Encephalitis
(EEE). To date, 124 birds have tested negative for either disease; 7
previously tested positive for West Nile Virus, including an American Crow
that was collected on Sherwood Drive in Westerly on 17 Aug 2000; and 2
previously tested positive for EEE. In addition, the presence of West Nile
Virus was previously reported in a horse, which was euthanized.
